import numpy as np
import pandas as pd
import seaborn as sns
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
sns.set(style="white", rc={"axes.facecolor": (0, 0, 0, 0)})

# Create the data
rs = np.random.RandomState(1979)
x = rs.randn(500)
g = np.tile(list("ABCDEFGHIJ"), 50)
df = pd.DataFrame(dict(x=x, g=g))
m = df.g.map(ord)
df["x"] += m

# Initialize the FacetGrid object
pal = sns.cubehelix_palette(10, rot=-.25, light=.7)
g = sns.FacetGrid(df, row="g", hue="g", aspect=15, size=.5, palette=pal)

# Draw the densities in a few steps
g.map(sns.kdeplot, "x", clip_on=False, shade=True, alpha=1, lw=1.5, bw=.2)
g.map(sns.kdeplot, "x", clip_on=False, color="w", lw=2, bw=.2)
g.map(plt.axhline, y=0, lw=2, clip_on=False)

# Define and use a simple function to label the plot in axes coordinates
def label(x, color, label):
    ax = plt.gca()
    ax.text(0, .2, label, fontweight="bold", color=color, 
            ha="left", va="center", transform=ax.transAxes)

g.map(label, "x")

# Set the subplots to overlap
g.fig.subplots_adjust(hspace=-.25)

# Remove axes details that don't play will with overlap
g.set_titles("")
g.set(yticks=[])
g.despine(bottom=True, left=True)

%python
''' Method for calculating Auto-cross-correlation

@Alexander Tureczek, 2018

Methods:

    auto_cros(data, lag=1)
        Purpose: Calculate the auto-cross-correlation 
        Input:

           DATA: data matrix, rows are used for correaltion calculation, columns equals time steps (lags)
           lag=1: Set the lag matrix to calculate. default = 1

        Output:  matrix of size row x row, with cross correlations. Diagonal is the autocorrelation.

    Source: http://ceur-ws.org/Vol-1425/paper4.pdf

'''

#Essential Import packages
import numpy as np
import pandas as pd


#test data 3x10 matrix
np.random.seed(42)
a1 = np.random.randint(1,10,10)

np.random.seed(41)
a2 = np.random.randint(1,10,10)

np.random.seed(43)
a3 = np.random.randint(1,10,10)

aa = np.array([a1,a2,a3])


#Auto cross correlation calculation by Lynne Billard
def auto_cros(data, lag=1):

    acf_cros = pd.DataFrame(index=range(data.shape[0]), columns=range(data.shape[0]))
    acf_cov = pd.DataFrame(index=range(data.shape[0]), columns=range(data.shape[0]))
    
    dif = data-data.mean(axis=1, keepdims=True)
    var_all = data.var(axis=1, keepdims=True)

    for i in range(data.shape[0]):
        
        start = np.array([dif[i][:-lag],]*data.shape[0])
        lag1 = dif[:,lag:]
        
        ac_cov= (start*lag1).mean(axis=1, keepdims=True)
        var_focus = data[i].var()
        var_pooled = np.sqrt(var_all*var_focus)
        acf_cros[i] = ac_cov/var_pooled

    return acf_cros 

print('Auto-Cross-Correlation')
print(auto_cros(aa, lag = 1))

%python
''' Method for calculating Auto-cross-correlation

@Alexander Tureczek, 2018

Methods:

    auto_cros(data, lag=1)
        Purpose: Calculate the auto-cross-correlation 
        Input:

           DATA: data matrix, rows are used for correaltion calculation, columns equals time steps (lags)
           lag=1: Set the lag matrix to calculate. default = 1

        Output:  matrix of size row x row, with cross correlations. Diagonal is the autocorrelation.

    Source: http://ceur-ws.org/Vol-1425/paper4.pdf

'''

#Essential Import packages
import numpy as np
import pandas as pd

#Freds sin eksempelkurver
# Define functions to be plottet for fun
flip = 1
x = np.linspace(0, 14, 100) # third value gives rough plots (10) or smooth plots (100)
for i in range(0, 2):
    y = np.sin(x + i * .5) * (7 - i) * flip
    Y[i] = y

#test data 3x10 matrix
a1 = Y[0]
a2 = Y[1]
a3=a2-a1

'''
# Testing auto cross correlation for 100% equal time series
a2=a1
a3=a1
# Conclussion - All values in the cross matices get 0.990989 (close to 1)
'''
aa = np.array([a1,a2,a3])



#Auto cross correlation calculation by Lynne Billard
def auto_cros(data, lag=1):

    acf_cros = pd.DataFrame(index=range(data.shape[0]), columns=range(data.shape[0]))
    acf_cov = pd.DataFrame(index=range(data.shape[0]), columns=range(data.shape[0]))
    
    dif = data-data.mean(axis=1, keepdims=True)
    var_all = data.var(axis=1, keepdims=True)

    for i in range(data.shape[0]):
        
        start = np.array([dif[i][:-lag],]*data.shape[0])
        lag1 = dif[:,lag:]
        
        ac_cov= (start*lag1).mean(axis=1, keepdims=True)
        var_focus = data[i].var()
        var_pooled = np.sqrt(var_all*var_focus)
        acf_cros[i] = ac_cov/var_pooled

    return acf_cros 

print('Auto-Cross-Correlation')
print(auto_cros(aa, lag = 1))
